<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910201-0086</DOCNO><DOCID>910201-0086.</DOCID><HL>   Reece Corp. Discloses   It Is in Negotiations   With Possible Buyer</HL><DATE>02/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5B</SO><CO>   RCE</CO><IN>FACTORY EQUIPMENT (FAC)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   WALTHAM, Mass. -- Reece Corp., a maker of industrialsewing machines, has put itself up for sale and said it is intalks with a party it didn't identify regarding the possiblepurchase of its common stock outstanding.   Reece said it hired BNY Associates, the investment bankingsubsidiary of Bank of New York, to assess the company's valueand advise and assist Reece in negotiations regarding thesale of the company.</LP><TEXT>   Reece has about 2.5 million shares outstanding, of which51% are held by Lawrie International Ltd. of Bermuda.   Reece's president and chief executive officer, Peter J.Abate, said: &quot;Given the current recession and difficultbusiness outlook in the world-wide apparel industry we serveand, consequently, the continuing operating losses we aresustaining as well as the increasing constraints on theavailability of credit, the board of directors will weighcarefully any proposal which may result from the currentdiscussions.&quot; However, he said there isn't any assurance thata sale of the company will be concluded.   In the nine months ended Sept. 29, Reece had a loss of$4.4 million, or $1.74 a share, on revenue of $39.4 million.Last May, Reece suspended payment of its quarterly dividendbecause of poor results and prospects for a continuedsluggish performance.   Reece said Bank of Boston and Shawmut Bank N.A. haveagreed to waive certain applications of loan covenants anddefer negotiations on its long-term bank debt and line ofcredit because of the ongoing sale discussions.</TEXT></DOC>